07611nam a22009615i 9781782047094DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820470947 a10.1515/97817820470942doi  a(DE-B1597)674840  a(OCoLC)1420507214  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aD117 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a909.0722300aStudies in Medievalism XXV :bMedievalism and Modernity /ced. by Karl Fugelso.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2016] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b6 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Medievalism ;v2500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tEditorial Note -- tI: Medievalism and Modernity: Some Perspective(s) -- tMedievalism at the End of History: Pessimism and Renewal in Just Visiting -- tMedieval Restoration and Modern Creativity -- tCrusader Medievalism and Modernity in Britain: The Most Noble Order of Crusaders and the Rupture of the First World War, 1921–49 -- tFrom the Republica Christiana to the “Great Revolution”: Middle Ages and Modernity in António Sardinha’s Writings (1914–25) -- tMoving through Time and Space in Mercedes Rubio’s Las siete muchachas del Liceo (1957) via Wagner’s Parsifal in Barcelona, Spain (1914) -- tII: Medievalist Visions -- tIntroduction -- tIn/visible Medieval/isms -- tArt, Heritage Industries, and the Legacy of William Morris in Michel Houellebecq’s The Map and the Territory -- tTravel in Space, Travel in Time: Michael Morrow’s Approach to Performing Medieval Music in the 1960s -- tImagining Medieval Chester: Practicebased Medievalism, Scholarship, and Creativity -- tThe Anachronic Middle Ages: Public Art, Cultural Memory, and the Medievalist Imagination -- tMedievalisms of Moral Panic: Borrowing the Past to Frame Fear in the Present -- tExtra-Temporal Place Attachment and Adaptive Reuse: The Afterlives of Medieval English Anchorholds -- tHere Be Dragons: Mapping Space and Time, Medieval and Modern -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays examining the complex intertwining and effect of medievalism on modernity - and vice versa.The question of how modernity has influenced medievalism and how medievalism has influenced modernity is the theme of this volume. The opening essays examine the 2001 film Just Visiting's comments on modern anxieties via medievalism; conflations of modernity with both medievalism and the Middle Ages in rewriting sources; the emergence of modernity amid the post-World War I movement The Most Noble Order of Crusaders; António Sardinha's promotion of medievalism as an antidote to modernity; and Mercedes Rubio's medievalism in her feminist commentary on modernity. The eight subsequent articles build on this foundation while discussing remnants of medieval London amid its moderndescendant; Michel Houellebecq's critique of medievalism through his 2011 novel La Carte et le territoire; historical authenticity in Michael Morrow's approach to performing medieval music; contemporary concerns in Ford Madox Brown and David Gentleman's murals; medieval Chester in Catherine A.M. Clarke and Nayan Kulkarni's Hryre (2012); medieval influences on the formation of and debate about modern moral panics; medievalist considerations inmodern repurposings of medieval anchorholds; and medieval sources for Paddy Molloy's Here Be Dragons (2013). The articles thus test the essays' methods and conclusions, even as the essays offer fresh perspectives on the articles. Karl Fugelso is Professor of Art History at Towson University in Baltimore, Maryland. Contributors: Edward Breen, Katherine A. Brown, Catherine A.M. Clarke, Louise D'Arcens, Joshua Davies, John LanceGriffith, Mike Horswell, Pedro Martins, Paddy Molloy, Lisa Nalbone, Sarah Salih, Michelle M. Sauer, James L. Smith  aMode of ac